-- id=36: Koeberg Nuclear Power Plant Long-Term Operation Extension
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'Koeberg Nuclear Power Station, South Africa''s only nuclear plant (supplying approximately 4–5% of national capacity from its two 900 MW units), received approval in 2023 for a 20-year Long-Term Operation (LTO) extension, taking the plant to 2044 and 2045 respectively. The National Nuclear Regulator (NNR) issued the renewed operating licence following a R20 billion refurbishment programme, including replacement of Koeberg''s steam generators by Framatome under a technically complex project that experienced delays and cost overruns. The LTO is fiscally critical: Koeberg produces baseload electricity at a marginal cost well below new-build alternatives, and its retention avoids the need for 1,800 MW of replacement capacity at a cost of R60–80 billion. The PC on Electricity and the NERSA review process both scrutinised the safety case and ageing management programme. Eskom''s nuclear operating subsidiary must maintain NNR compliance through a rolling 10-year safety case, with biennial inspections. The LTO also demonstrates institutional capacity for SA''s planned nuclear new build.',
  key_quote = 'Koeberg''s long-term operation extension preserves 1,800 MW of low-carbon, low-marginal-cost baseload power that would cost R80 billion to replace—its safe operation is a fiscal and climate imperative. — NNR Licence Decision, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Eskom / National Nuclear Regulator / Department of Mineral Resources and Energy',
  feasibility_note = 'Approved and underway. NNR licence issued; steam generator replacement completed. Risk is operational: any unplanned outage on ageing equipment has major grid impact. Regulatory compliance is the ongoing governance challenge.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 36;

-- id=37: Nuclear New Build Programme — 2,500 MW New Nuclear Sites
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s Integrated Resource Plan (IRP 2023/24) includes 2,500 MW of new nuclear capacity as part of the baseload mix, a policy direction endorsed by Cabinet in 2024 following two decades of contested proposals (the Zuma-era R1 trillion nuclear deal collapsed in 2017 after court rulings and public outcry). The current programme, led by DMRE in consultation with the National Nuclear Energy Executive Coordination Committee (NNEECC), envisages a competitive procurement process for small modular reactors (SMRs) or conventional light-water reactors at sites including Thyspunt (Eastern Cape) and Bantamsklip. The MTBPS 2025 does not allocate direct capital but notes the programme is to be financed through the Eskom balance sheet or a dedicated project vehicle with an independent power producer (IPP) structure. International technology suppliers (Westinghouse, EDF, Rosatom, CGNPC, NuScale, Holtec) have all engaged with the DMRE process. The NNR capacity constraints for new-build oversight (id=48) are the regulatory bottleneck. A government financial guarantee of R100–200 billion would be required for any conventional new-build under current debt structures.',
  key_quote = 'New nuclear is the only technology that can provide firm, dispatchable, zero-carbon baseload at scale—but the financing structure must avoid repeating the Zuma-era approach that nearly cost SA its investment grade rating. — DMRE Nuclear Procurement Framework, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy / Eskom / National Nuclear Regulator',
  feasibility_note = 'Long-term horizon, high fiscal risk. Procurement framework under design. SMR pathway lower-risk than conventional. NNR regulatory capacity and financing structure are the critical path constraints.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 37;

-- id=38: NERSA Municipal Tariff Rationalization and Cost-Reflective Pricing
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s 177 municipal electricity distributors charge widely varying tariffs—ranging from under R1.50/kWh to over R3.50/kWh for identical consumer categories—reflecting historical cost structures, cross-subsidisation practices, and varying degrees of Eskom bulk tariff pass-through. NERSA''s Municipal Tariff Approval process (under the Electricity Regulation Act) is meant to enforce cost-reflectivity, but municipalities routinely submit non-compliant tariffs and NERSA lacks effective enforcement mechanisms. The reform proposes: a standardised tariff methodology for all municipal distributors, mandatory disclosure of distribution losses (currently ranging from 8% to over 30%), a cross-subsidy lifeline tariff (LIFELOT) protected by regulation, and NERSA enforcement powers including tariff disallowance. The PC on Electricity''s BRRRs 2022–2024 document widespread non-compliance and note that unaffordable municipal electricity tariffs suppress demand and accelerate the shift to self-generation, undermining the municipal revenue base in a self-reinforcing cycle. This reform is also linked to EDI restructuring and the proposed Regional Electricity Distributors (REDs) programme.',
  key_quote = 'Municipal electricity tariffs vary by over 100% for equivalent consumers across SA—a regulatory failure that drives energy poverty, suppresses industrial investment in high-tariff areas, and accelerates the death spiral of distribution utilities. — NERSA Municipal Tariff Review, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'NERSA / National Treasury / Department of Cooperative Governance / Municipalities',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. NERSA has the regulatory mandate but lacks enforcement capacity and political backing. Municipal revenue protection creates resistance. National Treasury''s conditional grant framework can create compliance incentives.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 38;

-- id=39: Integrated Energy Plan Update — Gas and Energy Diversification
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Integrated Energy Plan (IEP) is South Africa''s comprehensive energy policy document, covering all energy forms—electricity, liquid fuels, gas, renewables, and bioenergy—over a 20-year horizon. The most recent IEP was published in 2017; an update incorporating the Gas Amendment Bill framework, LNG import plans, the revised IRP 2024 electricity mix, and the green hydrogen commercialisation strategy has been in draft since 2022. The updated IEP is required to set the policy framework for: the Gas Infrastructure Development Designation (selecting ports for LNG import terminals), the transition from coal-to-liquids (Sasol''s Secunda operations face carbon tax escalation that threatens viability), the role of gas peakers in balancing variable renewable energy, and the long-term hydrogen economy transition. The DMRE''s IEP process involves multi-stakeholder consultation (NERSA, DMRE, National Treasury, IDC, CEF). The 2025 MTBPS fiscal framework references the IEP update as the precondition for the gas infrastructure investment programme.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s energy transition cannot be managed by an electricity plan alone—the IEP update must address the coal-to-gas-to-hydrogen transition in liquid fuels, industrial heat, and transport simultaneously. — DMRE IEP Consultation Document, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy / CEF / NERSA',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win: gazetting the IEP update is a ministerial act. Delays are coordination-related across DMRE sub-divisions. Linked directly to Gas Amendment Bill and Sasol transition planning. No new legislation required.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 39;

-- id=40: NERSA Institutional Independence and Regulatory Capacity
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The National Energy Regulator of South Africa (NERSA) is constituted as an independent regulator under the National Energy Regulator Act (2004), with jurisdiction over electricity, piped gas, and petroleum pipelines. However, NERSA''s effective independence has been repeatedly questioned: tariff decisions are contested by Eskom and municipalities through courts and political processes, NERSA''s budget is approved through the National Assembly (creating political exposure), and its regulatory methodology for the electricity sector has not been updated to handle a competitive multi-generator market. The ERA Amendment Act (2024) dramatically expands NERSA''s mandate—it must now regulate third-party grid access, license dozens of new generators, and oversee the emerging wholesale electricity market—without a commensurate increase in regulatory staff or funding. The reform proposes: full budget autonomy (funded through licensee fees, not Parliament), a dedicated market regulation division for competitive electricity markets, and independent judicial appointment of NERSA commissioners (removing ministerial discretion). The World Bank and International Energy Agency have both flagged regulatory independence as a key risk to SA''s energy transition credibility.',
  key_quote = 'NERSA cannot regulate a competitive electricity market with a budget approved by Parliament, commissioners appointed by the Minister, and methodology designed for a single monopoly—institutional reform of the regulator is as important as market reform itself. — World Bank Energy Sector Report, South Africa, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'National Energy Regulator of South Africa / Department of Mineral Resources and Energy',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. Legislative amendment to NERA required. Political resistance from DMRE to ceding commissioner appointment power. ERA Amendment Act creates urgency—NERSA must expand capacity rapidly regardless of governance reform.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 40;

-- id=43: Gas Amendment Bill — LNG Import Infrastructure and City Gas
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s Gas Amendment Bill, passed by the National Assembly in 2024, replaces the Gas Act (2001) and creates the framework for a competitive gas market, LNG import and regasification infrastructure, and city gas distribution networks. The Bill designates two LNG import ports (Coega and Richards Bay are the preferred sites), establishes a gas systems operator function under NERSA, and creates a Gas Development Fund (seeded with R2 billion from the CEF) to subsidise gas pipeline extension to industrial corridors. The policy context is urgent: South Africa''s gas supply from Mozambique''s Pande/Temane fields (through the Sasol pipeline) is declining, and Sasol''s Secunda synthetic fuels plant faces existential carbon cost pressure by 2030. Gas peaker plants under the IRP procurement programme require domestic gas supply infrastructure that does not yet exist. The MTBPS 2025 identifies gas infrastructure as a priority within the R1 trillion infrastructure programme, with DBSA providing bridge financing for the first LNG terminal. The CEF (Central Energy Fund) is the designated public project developer.',
  key_quote = 'Gas will serve as the essential bridge between South Africa''s coal economy and its renewable future—but only if the LNG import infrastructure is built in the next five years, before the Mozambique supply declines critically. — CEF Gas Strategy, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy / Central Energy Fund / NERSA',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, medium-term horizon. Gas Amendment Bill enacted. LNG terminal procurement underway. Gas peaker capacity in IRP creates demand signal for investment. Mozambique political stability is an upstream supply risk.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 43;

-- id=62: National Transmission Company Capitalisation and Grid Expansion
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The National Transmission Company of South Africa (NTCSA) was legally established in 2024 as Eskom''s legally separate transmission subsidiary, in fulfilment of the Eskom restructuring conditions under the ERA Amendment Act and the debt relief framework. However, financial capitalisation—estimated at R40–60 billion to establish NTCSA as an entity that can borrow independently, invest in grid expansion, and function as a genuine independent system operator—has not yet occurred. Without capitalisation, NTCSA cannot enter the financial markets required to fund the R180 billion Transmission Development Plan, and the competitive electricity market cannot function because NTCSA remains financially dependent on Eskom Group. The reform covers: the NTCSA capitalisation plan (likely through a rights issue with government as anchor investor, or a Development Finance Institution loan), the staff and skills transfer from Eskom Transmission, the integration of the System Operator and Market Operator functions, and the independent governance arrangements under a new NTCSA board. The MTBPS 2025 links R254 billion Eskom debt relief tranches to NTCSA capitalisation milestones.',
  key_quote = 'An NTCSA that remains financially inside Eskom is an unbundling in name only—capitalisation is the moment when the transmission company becomes real, and the competitive electricity market becomes possible. — Eskom Restructuring Implementation Review, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Eskom / NTCSA / National Treasury / DMRE',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, complex execution. Capitalisation structure requires National Treasury, PIC, and DFI coordination. Staff transfer and governance establishment are on critical path. Target: NTCSA financial independence by 2026/27.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 62;

