-- id=62: National Transmission Company Capitalisation and Grid Expansion
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The National Transmission Company South Africa (NTCSA) was formally established in October 2024, separating the grid business from Eskom''s generation and distribution functions. It faces an enormous infrastructure task: the Transmission Development Plan (TDP) requires 14,500 km of new high-voltage lines and 210 transformers providing 133,000 MVA of new capacity between 2025 and 2034, at an estimated cost of R490 billion (~$22 billion). Without this investment, renewable energy projects across the Northern and Western Cape cannot connect to the grid, leaving signed IPP agreements stranded. Seven priority Independent Transmission Projects (ITPs) — including the Aries-Aggeneis 400 kV line and Groeipunt upgrades — went to RFP in November 2025 via the IPP Office, with a Credit Guarantee Vehicle to de-risk private investment expected to launch in early 2026. The South African Wholesale Electricity Market (SAWEM) is scheduled to launch in April 2026, requiring NTCSA to act as market operator. NERSA''s revenue determination for NTCSA''s first regulatory period will be pivotal: under-recovery would force NTCSA back toward state funding, while over-recovery raises tariffs on already-strained households and municipalities. The 2025 MTBPS and Budget 2026 allocated R5.2 billion in equity support to NTCSA over the medium term.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa needs R490 billion in new transmission infrastructure over the next decade — capital that cannot come from the fiscus alone; private investment under transparent regulation is the only viable path. — DBSA Transmission Infrastructure Report, 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Electricity and Energy / Eskom / NTCSA / NERSA',
  feasibility_note = 'High growth impact; moderate feasibility. Legislative base is the Electricity Regulation Amendment Act (2024). Key risks: NERSA tariff adequacy, NTCSA governance as a new entity, grid connection queue backlog. Operation Vulindlela has this as a Priority 1 deliverable.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 62;

-- id=38: NERSA Municipal Tariff Rationalization and Cost-Reflective Pricing
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa has 178 licensed electricity distributors, most of them municipalities, and their tariff structures have historically been opaque, cross-subsidised, and misaligned with actual cost of supply (CoS). NERSA''s multi-year effort to enforce CoS compliance reached a landmark in the 2025/26 financial year: for the first time, all 178 licensees submitted CoS studies, up from just 34 in 2020/21 and 76 in 2024/25. This shift is required under the Electricity Pricing Policy and codified in the Electricity Regulation Amendment Act. NERSA approved an 11.32% Eskom tariff increase for local authorities in FY2026 (effective 1 April 2025), with a further 9.01% approved for FY2027. Eskom is implementing simplified and transparent tariff structures from 1 April 2025 to remove unintended subsidies across customer categories. The key structural challenge remains that many municipalities use electricity revenue surpluses to cross-subsidise rates, water, and refuse services — an arrangement that is fiscally unsustainable as distributed solar erodes the municipal customer base. The Electricity Regulation Amendment Act explicitly links municipal tariff reform to the broader market restructuring, including open access and the NTCSA''s role as an independent transmission operator.',
  key_quote = 'For the first time in NERSA''s history, every licensed electricity distributor has submitted a cost-of-supply study — a foundational step toward tariffs that reflect real costs rather than cross-subsidies. — NERSA Media Statement, January 2025',
  responsible_department = 'NERSA / National Treasury / COGTA / SALGA',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. NERSA has achieved full CoS compliance for the first time, providing the data foundation. Political resistance from municipalities dependent on electricity surpluses remains the key constraint. Phased implementation supported by SALGA collaboration.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 38;

-- id=43: Gas Amendment Bill — LNG Import Infrastructure and City Gas
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa faces a structural gas supply crisis: industrial gas consumption is concentrated around Sasol''s Secunda operations, which are declining, and analysts warn the country could run out of industrial gas by 2028, putting 70,000 jobs at risk in downstream industries. The Gas Bill 2026 (B6-2026), introduced to Parliament in early 2026 to replace the Gas Act 2001, explicitly incorporates liquefied natural gas (LNG) as a regulated technology for the first time and strengthens NERSA''s licensing and enforcement powers. In parallel, Transnet National Ports Authority (TNPA) and Zululand Energy Terminal have signed an agreement to develop an LNG terminal at Richards Bay with an initial capacity of 2 million tonnes per annum (mtpa), with a floating storage and regasification unit (FSRU) in Phase 1; a final investment decision is expected in 2026. The broader gas-to-power agenda includes a 3,000 MW gas power project at Richards Bay and conversion of Eskom''s Ankerlig and Gourikwa peaker plants from distillate to gas. NERSA introduced streamlined licensing rules for small-scale compressed natural gas (CNG) and LNG virtual pipelines in 2025 to accelerate city-level gas networks. Despite 21 years of planning for LNG import infrastructure, no project has yet reached financial close, making the 2026 FID at Richards Bay the critical near-term test.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa will run out of industrial gas by 2028 — this is not a distant threat. Without LNG import infrastructure, manufacturing industries will face unplanned shutdowns and 70,000 jobs are at risk. — The Conversation, March 2026',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy / NERSA / Transnet National Ports Authority',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. The Gas Bill 2026 provides updated legislative foundation; Richards Bay terminal FID is the immediate trigger. Long history of failed LNG proposals creates credibility risk. Union and environmental stakeholder positions require management.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 43;

-- id=36: Koeberg Nuclear Power Plant Long-Term Operation Extension
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'Koeberg, the only nuclear power station on the African continent, delivers approximately 5% of South Africa''s electricity (1.9 GW combined capacity) at a marginal cost well below new-build alternatives. Eskom''s long-term operation (LTO) programme has now secured regulatory approval for both units: the National Nuclear Regulator (NNR) approved a 20-year life extension for Unit 1 in July 2024 (now licensed to July 2044), and NERSA approved a further 20-year extension for Unit 2 in November 2025 (licensed to 2045). Unit 2 was reconnected to the grid on 30 December 2024 following completion of extensive maintenance including replacement of steam generators. Unit 1 commenced its restart sequence in September 2025 after a scheduled refuelling and maintenance outage, delivering 930 MW back to the grid. The LTO programme involved R30+ billion in capital investment including replacement of reactor internals, steam generators, and digital instrumentation. The IAEA conducted a Long Term Operation Safety Review (SALTO) mission at Koeberg in 2024. Despite earlier concerns about construction quality and procurement delays, the NNR process was ultimately completed, providing South Africa with reliable low-carbon baseload generation through the mid-2040s — a period during which the IRP anticipates the dominance of variable renewable sources that require dispatchable backup.',
  key_quote = 'Koeberg''s 20-year life extension provides South Africa with its lowest-cost dispatchable baseload generation through to 2045, avoiding the full cost of replacement capacity at current construction prices. — World Nuclear Association, South Africa Profile, 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Eskom / National Nuclear Regulator / Department of Electricity and Energy',
  feasibility_note = 'High feasibility: regulatory approvals now granted for both units. Investment already committed. Key ongoing risks are ageing plant reliability and Eskom''s ability to sustain qualified nuclear engineering staff during load-shedding recovery period.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 36;

-- id=105: PEPFAR Funding Transition — Domestic HIV/AIDS Programme Financing
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa has the world''s largest HIV treatment programme, with approximately 5.7 million people on antiretroviral therapy (ART). The PEPFAR (President''s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief) programme has provided roughly $450 million annually — funding 15,374 HIV response staff across national and 27 priority districts and supporting approximately 222,000 people on ART including 7,445 children. In January 2025, the Trump administration issued an executive order freezing all US foreign aid for 90 days. A transitional agreement negotiated in October 2025 provides only $115 million for the October 2025 – March 2026 period, a 75% reduction, leaving a R4.6 billion (~$250 million) immediate HR cost gap. South Africa currently funds 77% of its AIDS response domestically; the 2025 Budget Review includes a 3.3% annual increase for HIV and TB programmes over three years, but this falls far short of replacing PEPFAR at scale. UNAIDS estimates that without mitigation, the funding freeze could cause 500,000 additional HIV infections and 300,000 AIDS-related deaths in SA over five years. The DoH has reprioritised domestic ART budgets and is engaging Global Fund to bridge gaps. The NHI framework, once operational, is intended to provide a vehicle for consolidated domestic health financing that would eventually reduce PEPFAR dependency, but implementation remains years away.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa funds 77% of its AIDS response — but the remaining 23% from PEPFAR covers the most marginalised populations. A rapid transition without adequate domestic substitution would reverse two decades of progress. — UNAIDS, February 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Health / National Treasury / South African National AIDS Council (SANAC)',
  feasibility_note = 'Urgent fiscal challenge. Short-term: bridge financing from Global Fund and domestic reallocation. Medium-term: DoH must absorb ~R4.6 billion in PEPFAR staffing costs. NHI implementation timeline (5–10 years) does not solve the immediate gap. Political sensitivity given US-SA diplomatic tensions in 2025.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 105;

-- id=22: Two-Pot Pension System — Retirement Savings Architecture Reform
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s Two-Pot Retirement System came into effect on 1 September 2024, representing the most significant structural reform to the country''s R6 trillion retirement savings industry in decades. Under the new architecture, all contributions made after 1 September 2024 are split: one-third into an accessible Savings Component (minimum withdrawal R2,000, once per tax year, taxed at marginal rate) and two-thirds into a locked Retirement Component inaccessible before retirement. Existing balances are preserved in a Vested Component. To seed the savings pot at inception, up to 10% of existing retirement fund balances (capped at R30,000) were transferred to the savings pot. Uptake was immediate and substantial: within the first 10 days, 160,000 withdrawal applications were submitted totalling R4.1 billion; by October 2024 this had grown to 1.2 million applications releasing approximately R21 billion. SARS collected significant tax revenue on these withdrawals. The reform addressed South Africa''s chronic problem of pension fund leakage on resignation — previously workers cashed out their entire retirement savings when changing jobs — by allowing partial liquidity without forfeiting the retirement component. Members aged 55 and older as of 1 March 2021 had until 31 August 2025 to opt in. The PFA, Income Tax Act, and Pension Funds Act were all amended to give effect to the reform.',
  key_quote = 'Within two months of launch, 1.2 million South Africans withdrew R21 billion from their savings pots — demonstrating both the liquidity need the reform addresses and the scale of the retirement industry''s transition. — National Treasury, October 2024',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / Financial Sector Conduct Authority / South African Revenue Service',
  feasibility_note = 'High feasibility: fully implemented since September 2024. Legislative and regulatory frameworks in place. Key ongoing risk is that high early withdrawal rates may reduce retirement adequacy — monitoring by FSCA and Treasury is ongoing. Second phase (auto-enrolment for informal workers) still pending.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 22;

-- id=28: Carbon Tax Phase 2 Implementation and Revenue Use
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s Carbon Tax entered Phase 2 on 1 January 2026, running through to 31 December 2030. The headline rate increased from R236 to R308 per tonne of CO₂e — a 31% step-up and the largest single increase since the tax was introduced in 2019 — with a legislated trajectory to R462 per tonne by 2030. From 1 April 2026 the carbon fuel levy increases to 19c/litre on petrol and 23c/litre on diesel. The basic tax-free allowance is maintained at 60% through 2030, and the carbon offset allowance increases by 5 percentage points (to 10% for fugitive/process emissions and 15% for combustion emissions) from January 2026. Annual carbon tax revenue is estimated at R1.5 billion — modest relative to the economy — because the large tax-free allowances and offset system reduce the effective rate substantially. Critics argue the effective rate remains too low to drive meaningful abatement; supporters note the importance of maintaining economic competitiveness and aligning with the Just Energy Transition commitments. Revenue is recycled through the electricity generation levy credit, the renewable energy premium credit, and the energy efficiency savings incentive. The EU''s Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism (CBAM), which begins full implementation in 2026, creates a direct trade incentive for SA exporters — particularly in steel, aluminium, and cement — to reduce their carbon intensity.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s carbon tax rate rises to R308 per tonne of CO₂e from January 2026 — the highest since inception — but with a 60% tax-free allowance, most firms face an effective rate of R123/tonne, far below the social cost of carbon. — ENS Africa Tax Brief, 2025',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / South African Revenue Service / Department of Forestry, Fisheries and the Environment',
  feasibility_note = 'High feasibility: Phase 2 commenced January 2026 per schedule. Key implementation challenge is expanding the offset market and ensuring offset quality. CBAM compatibility provides external pressure to strengthen the effective rate over time. Revenue use transparency remains a stakeholder concern.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 28;

-- id=50: NSFAS Sustainable Funding Model — Comprehensive Post-School Student Finance
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) is South Africa''s primary vehicle for funding post-school education for students from households earning under R350,000 annually. In the 2025 academic year the scheme approved funding for over 626,000 first-time applicants, but faces structural financial collapse: the 2025 budget deficit grew from R11.6 billion to approximately R14 billion after second-semester registrations, driven by over-subscription relative to appropriated funds. A serious governance breach led SARS to terminate its data-sharing relationship with NSFAS, forcing the scheme to use less accurate credit bureau data for 2025 income verification — increasing both errors and fraud risk. Private student accommodation providers report payments delayed by months, threatening the financial viability of student housing. A Cabinet-level technical team comprising DHET, NSFAS, National Treasury, DPME, and the Presidency was appointed in mid-2025 to design enrolment planning reforms and a sustainable funding framework, with findings due to Cabinet by end-2025. The Budget 2026 allocates R57.6 billion to NSFAS over the MTEF but without a structural solution to the open-ended entitlement. Proposals include means-testing reform, graduate income-contingent repayment for higher-income beneficiaries, TVET vs. university differentiated funding models, and stronger enrolment planning caps.',
  key_quote = 'NSFAS''s R14 billion deficit represents a structural funding gap — not an administrative problem. Without a fundamental redesign of the eligibility model and repayment architecture, the scheme will crowd out other post-school education budgets entirely. — DHET Parliamentary Briefing, 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Higher Education and Training / National Treasury / NSFAS Board',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. Political pressure against any restriction of the "fee-free" commitment is intense. Technical team process underway offers a reform pathway. IMF 2025 Article IV mission flagged NSFAS as a contingent fiscal risk. Legislative changes to the NSFAS Act will be required for structural solutions.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 50;

-- id=76: PRASA Passenger Rail Recovery Programme
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'PRASA''s (Passenger Rail Agency of South Africa) commuter rail network collapsed during COVID-19 and preceding years of theft, vandalism, and governance failure — by 2021 fewer than 10 corridors were operating and rolling stock was deliberately torched. The recovery programme, backed by R21+ billion in fleet procurement (X''trapolis and Gibela-built Afro 4000 trains), has made measurable progress: by end-May 2025, 35 of 40 planned corridors were commissioned, annual audited passenger journeys reached 77 million, and train punctuality improved from 81% to 87.4% in 2024/25, while cancellations fell from 7.2% to 4.6%. In 2024, 39.44 million trips were recorded — double the target and 152% above the prior year. PRASA is now inviting private sector participation to modernise the network. Long-distance mainline service reintroductions are planned for 2026/27 on routes including Johannesburg–Durban, Cape Town–Johannesburg, and Johannesburg–Musina. The Budget 2026 allocates R32.5 billion to PRASA over the MTEF for operations, maintenance, and fleet. Key ongoing challenges include infrastructure deterioration on restored corridors, persistent vandalism requiring security expenditure, fleet shortages limiting frequency, and the need for a long-term PPP model for regional rail expansion.',
  key_quote = 'PRASA has reconnected 35 of 40 corridors and logged 77 million passenger journeys in 2025 — a genuine recovery from near-total collapse, though sustained performance requires capital investment the agency cannot finance alone. — PRASA Annual Report, 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / PRASA / Department of Public Enterprises',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate-high feasibility for continued recovery. Fleet delivery and corridor restoration are on track. Structural financial sustainability requires fare revenue growth and private sector co-investment in maintenance. Vandalism and theft remain the hardest-to-solve operational risks.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 76;

-- id=5: EV White Paper — Managed Automotive Transition
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s automotive manufacturing industry accounts for 2.9% of GDP and R200+ billion in annual exports (12.4% of total export value), making it the largest single manufacturing sector. The EV White Paper, released by DTIC on 5 December 2023, charts a managed transition from internal combustion engine (ICE) vehicles to a dual-platform strategy (ICE + EV production) by 2035, emphasising production and export in Phase 1 and domestic demand stimulation in Phase 2. The policy directly responds to EU and UK import market shifts toward EV-only sales deadlines (2035). A landmark new investment incentive effective 1 March 2026 allows automotive producers to claim 150% of qualifying EV and hydrogen-powered vehicle investment in the first year, supplementing the existing Automotive Production and Development Programme (APDP Phase 2). The first domestically assembled EVs are expected by 2026, with Toyota, BMW, VW, Ford, and Isuzu having manufacturing footprints in South Africa. Challenges include the domestic electricity supply (ironically, load-shedding reduces EV attractiveness for consumers) and the absence of a domestic battery manufacturing ecosystem. The White Paper links to Critical Minerals Beneficiation (PGMs for fuel cells), the Green Hydrogen Commercialisation Strategy, and the JET Investment Plan.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s EV White Paper commits the country to a dual-platform automotive strategy by 2035 — protecting R200 billion in annual export revenue while positioning SA as a continental EV manufacturing hub. — DTIC, December 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Trade, Industry and Competition / Automotive Industry Development Centre / NAACAM',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. OEM investment decisions are the critical lever; the 150% capex allowance from March 2026 is the primary demand-side fiscal instrument. Domestic EV market demand is constrained by load-shedding, charging infrastructure gaps, and vehicle affordability.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 5;

-- id=77: Transport Economic Regulator — Operationalising the EROT Act
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Economic Regulation of Transport Act 6 of 2024 (EROT Act), promulgated on 11 June 2024, establishes South Africa''s first single Transport Economic Regulator (TER) covering road, rail, sea, and air — modelled on NERSA''s role in the energy sector. The TER''s core mandate is to approve price tariffs for regulated transport entities (primarily Transnet for ports and freight rail) to prevent monopolistic pricing and cross-subsidisation that has made SA''s logistics costs among the highest in the world. Phased commencement began in April 2025. The TER is designed to end the situation in which Transnet simultaneously operates, self-prices, and self-regulates its infrastructure — a key structural reason why Durban port container terminal productivity fell to among the lowest globally. NERSA''s analogous oversight of electricity has, despite imperfections, provided a more contestable regulatory space than transport. By mid-2025 Transnet reported a 10.7% improvement in port container handling, partly anticipating independent regulatory scrutiny. The EROT Act links directly to Operation Vulindlela''s logistics reform programme and the broader objective of restoring South Africa''s export competitiveness, particularly for minerals, agricultural products, and manufactured goods.',
  key_quote = 'The EROT Act ends the era in which Transnet set its own tariffs unchecked — independent economic regulation of transport is a precondition for the private sector investment the sector needs. — Bowmans Infrastructure Alert, June 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / Economic Regulation of Transport / Transnet / Ports Regulator',
  feasibility_note = 'High feasibility: Act promulgated, commencement underway. Key implementation risk is standing up the TER with sufficient technical expertise to set credible tariffs for complex multi-modal infrastructure. Transnet''s cooperation with the tariff review process is critical.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 77;

-- id=2: Competition Commission Digital Markets Inquiry
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Competition Commission of South Africa has pursued two parallel digital market inquiries with significant 2025 outcomes. The Media and Digital Platforms Market Inquiry (MDPMI), closed on 24 February 2025, found that Google extracted R300–500 million in value annually from South African news publishers in 2023 through zero-click search results and algorithmic designs that favour foreign over local media. The Commission secured a R688 million commitment from Google over five years to support local news sustainability through content licensing, innovation grants, and capacity-building. The inquiry also flagged generative AI as a new threat to news publisher revenue, proposing opt-out rights and mandatory content licensing frameworks. Separately, the Online Intermediation Platforms Market Inquiry examined market power in e-commerce, app stores, and digital advertising. The 2025 Kluwer Competition Law review identified ongoing investigations into accommodation, food delivery, and ride-hailing platforms. The Commission''s approach parallels Australia''s News Media Bargaining Code and the EU''s Digital Markets Act, adapting these frameworks for South Africa''s media and competition law architecture. Digital advertising concentration — Google and Meta capturing 70%+ of digital ad revenue — directly undermines the fiscal sustainability of local journalism, a democratic public goods concern beyond narrow competition law.',
  key_quote = 'Google extracted R300–500 million from South African news publishers in 2023 while reducing referral traffic — the MDPMI secured R688 million in commitments to restore a measure of value equity. — Competition Commission MDPMI Provisional Report, February 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Competition Commission / Competition Tribunal / Department of Trade, Industry and Competition',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. The MDPMI outcome sets a precedent for negotiated remedies; full regulatory frameworks for AI content and digital advertising require legislative development. Large platforms have legal resources to contest recommendations aggressively.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 2;

-- id=115: Government SMME Procurement — Enforcing the 30% Set-Aside
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s Public Procurement Act 28 of 2024, signed by President Ramaphosa on 23 July 2024, replaces the fragmented procurement regime of the Preferential Procurement Policy Framework Act (PPPFA) and associated regulations. The Act establishes a Public Procurement Office (PPO) within National Treasury as a centralised standard-setting and compliance body issuing binding instructions across all organs of state. Critically, it creates a statutory "Set-Aside" mechanism allowing the Minister of Finance — or organs of state themselves — to designate specific contracts exclusively for SMMEs, youth-owned enterprises, women-owned businesses, and enterprises in specific localities or townships. The government''s stated commitment to direct at least 30% of public procurement spending toward SMMEs and cooperatives is now to be operationalised through these Set-Asides once the implementing regulations are finalised. Regulation drafting continued through 2025-2026 under public comment processes. MAPS (Methodology for Assessing Procurement Systems) assessment in 2024 identified procurement transparency, internal controls, and SMME payment timelines as areas requiring improvement. The Act also codifies 30-day payment terms for SMMEs, addressing the chronic late-payment problem that has caused widespread SMME insolvencies.',
  key_quote = 'The Public Procurement Act 2024 gives South Africa its first unified, modern procurement framework — the 30% SMME Set-Aside, once regulations are final, will be a statutory obligation, not a ministerial preference. — National Treasury, July 2024',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / Public Procurement Office / Department of Small Business Development',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. Legislative foundation is in place. Finalisation of regulations and PPO operationalisation are the critical path. Enforcement capacity across thousands of procurement entities is the long-term challenge. Success in 30-day payment compliance would have immediate impact on SMME survival rates.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 115;

-- id=112: Health Market Inquiry — Private Sector Reforms Implementation
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Competition Commission''s Health Market Inquiry (HMI) Final Report (2019) found that South Africa''s private healthcare market is characterised by excessive pricing, overutilisation, inadequate regulation, and market power concentration among large hospital groups and funders — producing a system where private medical scheme membership costs roughly 10–15% of household income for middle-class families. Implementation has been slow: on 14 February 2025, Minister of Trade, Industry and Competition Parks Tau published draft "interim block exemption" regulations allowing collective multilateral tariff negotiations between medical schemes and providers — the first concrete regulatory step in six years. A multilateral negotiating and price-setting body under DoH oversight is proposed. Health Minister Motsoaledi cited National Treasury financial constraints as the reason an independent tariff regulatory authority has not been established. Stakeholder coalitions (UHAC — Universal Health Access Coalition) argue the "piecemeal" implementation only addresses tariff-setting but not market structure reforms around hospital accreditation, information transparency, or the Prescribed Minimum Benefits framework. Private healthcare costs are directly relevant to the NHI transition: as NHI begins to move medical scheme members into a unified pool, the pricing environment in the private sector will affect NHI''s fiscal sustainability.',
  key_quote = 'The draft interim block exemptions published in February 2025 represent the first substantive HMI implementation step — but implementing only selected recommendations risks entrenching the structural problems the Inquiry identified. — UHAC Statement, March 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Competition Commission / Department of Health / Department of Trade, Industry and Competition',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility for partial implementation; low feasibility for full structural reform. Treasury budget constraints limit the independent regulatory body option. NHI adds urgency — private sector pricing reform is a precondition for a viable NHI benefit design.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 112;

-- id=44: Upstream Petroleum Resources Development Bill
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Upstream Petroleum Resources Development Act, assented to by President Ramaphosa in November 2024, ends the decades-long legal ambiguity that governed petroleum exploration under the Mineral and Petroleum Resources Development Act (MPRDA). The Act separates the petroleum regime from mining, establishing a dedicated framework administered by the South African Agency for Promotion of Petroleum Exploration and Exploitation (SAAPEE). Key provisions include a 20% free-carry state participation right for PETROSA (the state oil company, formerly PetroSA) and mandatory black persons'' equity participation in exploration and production rights, modelled on the mining sector''s black economic empowerment requirements. The Act covers reconnaissance permits, exploration rights, production rights, and retention permits, providing greater regulatory certainty for international exploration companies. The timing is significant: TotalEnergies, Shell, and other majors have been exploring in the Orange Basin off the Southern African coast, with the Brulpadda and Luiperd fields (operated by TotalEnergies) representing potential multi-billion barrel reserves whose development has been delayed by legislative uncertainty. Gas discoveries in the Karoo and offshore could provide a domestic supply solution to the looming industrial gas shortage.',
  key_quote = 'President Ramaphosa''s assent to the Upstream Petroleum Resources Development Act in November 2024 provides the regulatory certainty that major offshore gas and oil projects have awaited for over a decade. — SAnews, November 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy / SAAPEE / PETROSA',
  feasibility_note = 'High feasibility for legislative foundation — Act now law. Implementation of SAAPEE as competent permitting authority is the near-term challenge. Black economic empowerment requirements may slow exploration investment; structured equity participation models (similar to mining industry precedents) will need to be developed.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 44;

-- id=52: SETA Reform and Skills Development Levy Efficiency
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s 21 Sector Education and Training Authorities (SETAs) collect approximately R20 billion per year from the 1% Skills Development Levy (SDL) on payrolls, employing nearly 3,000 staff — yet produced fewer than 100,000 certified individuals in 2023/24, a completion rate of roughly 5 people per R1 million in levy revenue. Finance Minister Godongwana''s 2026 Budget Speech explicitly committed to overhauling the SDL and SETA model, proposing a dual-training system modelled on Germany''s apprenticeship framework to shift toward work-integrated learning. Industry response has been broadly supportive: the IT sector (represented by PNet and others) welcomed the announcement as an acknowledgement that the current system produces qualifications without employability. Critics argue the dual-training proposal does not address the SETAs'' governance failures — procurement corruption, irregular expenditure, and political board appointments that consistently draw Auditor-General findings. The SDL reform intersects with the Presidential Youth Employment Intervention, the 30% youth wage subsidy debate, and Operation Vulindlela''s human capital agenda. The SETA system is also the primary vehicle for funding apprenticeship training in construction, engineering, and automotive — sectors central to infrastructure investment delivery.',
  key_quote = 'The SETA system collects R20 billion annually and employs 3,000 staff — but certified fewer than 100,000 people in 2023/24. The 2026 Budget commits to a fundamental overhaul; the question is whether governance reform follows the structural change. — IT-Online, February 2026',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Higher Education and Training / National Skills Authority / SETAs',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. Budget 2026 commitment creates political momentum. Legislative changes to the Skills Development Act and Skills Development Levies Act are required. Risk: dual-training announcement without governance reform repeats past SETA restructuring failures. SETA merger proposals have failed before.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 52;

-- id=113: African Medicines Agency Treaty Ratification and SAHPRA Strengthening
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The African Medicines Agency (AMA) was established under the African Union framework and opened its headquarters in Yaoundé, Cameroon in 2021 after South Africa ratified the AMA Treaty. SAHPRA (South African Health Products Regulatory Authority) — one of Africa''s most technically sophisticated medicines regulators — is positioned as a reference regulatory authority for the AMA framework, able to provide registration reliance mechanisms that allow other African countries to benefit from SAHPRA''s rigorous reviews. SAHPRA''s 2025-2030 Strategic Plan and 2025/26 Annual Performance Plan outline priorities including: implementing a fully risk-based assessment approach, reducing registration backlogs (critical for NHI benefit package design), strengthening post-market surveillance, and combating the proliferation of counterfeit pharmaceuticals and medical devices. On 30 September 2025, South Africa launched a National Action Plan on Substandard and Falsified Medical Products in partnership with WHO. SAHPRA is also refining its eCTD dossier submission standards and labelling requirements to align with international ICH guidelines, critical for attracting pharmaceutical manufacturers to register in South Africa as a gateway to African markets. The AMA-SAHPRA relationship represents South Africa''s most concrete contribution to African health system integration under the AU Agenda 2063 framework.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s ratification of the AMA Treaty and SAHPRA''s position as a reference regulatory authority creates the institutional architecture for safe, accessible medicines across Africa — but SAHPRA needs sustained investment to fulfil this role. — SAHPRA Strategic Plan 2025-2030',
  responsible_department = 'South African Health Products Regulatory Authority / Department of Health / Department of International Relations',
  feasibility_note = 'High feasibility for SAHPRA-specific reforms within existing legislative mandate. AMA integration pathway is longer-term and depends on AU member state buy-in. Key constraint: SAHPRA budget adequacy and staff retention in competition with private pharma industry.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 113;

-- id=107: TB Elimination National Acceleration Programme
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa carries the world''s fifth-highest TB incidence burden and the highest absolute case load in Africa. The TB incidence rate has declined by 57% from 988 per 100,000 in 2015 to 427 per 100,000 in 2023 — meeting the 2025 WHO End TB milestone — but the country remains far from elimination (defined as <10 per 100,000). The National TB Recovery Plan 4.0 (April 2025 – March 2026) and the National TB Strategic Plan 2023–2028 (Vision 2028) provide the implementation framework, deploying systematic community screening, TB Preventive Treatment (TPT), targeted next-generation sequencing for drug-resistant TB, shorter paediatric and DR-TB regimens, and differentiated care models. The 2024/25 budget allocated R4 billion for TB, with 71% from domestic sources, 21% from the Global Fund, and 8% from USAID''s ACCELERATE programme ($94 million over five years). However, the 2025 US foreign aid freeze disrupted USAID TB support, accelerating the shift to domestic financing: South Africa increased its domestic TB funding share to 81% in 2025/26. Drug-resistant TB (MDR/XDR-TB) remains the most acute challenge, with SA having one of the world''s highest DR-TB burdens, requiring expensive second- and third-line drug regimens that stress the pharmaceutical supply chain.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa achieved its 2025 End TB milestone with a 57% reduction in incidence from 2015 — but 427 per 100,000 is still 40 times the elimination threshold; the programme must sustain progress without PEPFAR and USAID support. — National TB Recovery Plan 4.0, May 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Health / South African Medical Research Council / National Institute for Communicable Diseases',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. Proven implementation framework exists; progress is measurable. Key risk is the USAID funding withdrawal in 2025 creating drug supply and personnel gaps. MDR-TB requires sustained pharmaceutical procurement that is vulnerable to rand/dollar exchange rate volatility.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 107;

-- id=118: Cannabis and Hemp Industry Licensing Rationalisation
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s cannabis and hemp sector sits at the intersection of agricultural development, industrial policy, public health regulation, and criminal justice reform. The regulatory landscape has been shifting rapidly: hemp was recognised as an agricultural crop in 2022, since when the Department of Agriculture has issued 2,031 cultivation permits. In December 2025, the permissible THC threshold for hemp plants was raised from 0.2% to 2%, significantly expanding the range of commercially viable cultivars. The Hemp and Cannabis Commercialisation Policy is expected to reach Cabinet for approval and public comment by April 2026. An Overarching Cannabis Bill — consolidating the Cannabis for Private Purposes Act (2024), commercial cultivation, manufacturing, and research regulations — is being drafted across DTIC, DAF, DoH, and DoJCD for presentation to Parliament by mid-2027. SAHPRA administers medicinal cannabis licensing. The Department of Trade, Industry and Competition''s National Cannabis Master Plan identifies export of medicinal cannabis to the EU, UK, and US as a priority revenue opportunity, with South Africa''s climate and soil conditions competitive with established producers in Colombia and Morocco. Provincial recognition frameworks for traditional cannabis growers — particularly in the Eastern Cape and KwaZulu-Natal — address social equity in the sector''s formalisation.',
  key_quote = 'Government is moving to unlock South Africa''s multibillion-rand cannabis and hemp sector — with the THC threshold increase, cultivation permits, and the Cannabis Commercialisation Policy converging in 2026 as the most active regulatory period in the sector''s history. — Sowetan, March 2026',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Trade, Industry and Competition / SAHPRA / Department of Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development / Department of Justice',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. Regulatory fragmentation across four departments creates coordination risk. SAHPRA licensing bottlenecks have frustrated early-stage industry participants. Export market opportunities are real but require phytosanitary and GMP compliance that most small producers cannot achieve independently.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 118;

-- id=81: SANRAL Road Funding Model Reform Post E-Tolls
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s e-toll system on Gauteng freeways was officially discontinued on 12 April 2024, after more than a decade of near-total public non-compliance. Gantries were physically disconnected; the Gauteng Freeway Improvement Project (GFIP) debt of approximately R20 billion is being settled 70% by National Treasury and 30% by the Gauteng Provincial Government. SANRAL''s traditional toll plazas continue to operate nationwide, with tariffs increased by 4.84% effective 1 March 2025. The e-toll episode exposed the fundamental challenge of road funding in South Africa: the fuel levy, historically the primary source of road maintenance revenue, is declining in real terms as vehicles become more fuel-efficient, and faces accelerating long-term erosion as EVs (which pay no fuel levy) gain market share. The Department of Transport is developing a Road Funding Policy that must address: the fiscal gap left by the fuel levy decline, the replacement revenue model for EVs and electric trucks, the equitable contribution of heavy freight vehicles that cause disproportionate road damage, and the feasibility of distance-based charging (a modern tolling concept) without repeating the political failure of e-tolls. The R1 trillion infrastructure programme requires SANRAL to maintain and expand the national road network, but its revenue base is structurally challenged.',
  key_quote = 'With e-tolls scrapped and the fuel levy declining as EVs enter the fleet, South Africa faces a road funding gap that will widen every year — the Road Funding Policy review is not optional; it is urgent. — OUTA Road Funding Analysis, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / SANRAL / National Treasury',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility for Road Funding Policy development; low-moderate for any form of user-pays charging given the e-toll political legacy. Distance-based charging for heavy freight offers the most politically viable near-term revenue supplement. Full EV road-charging framework requires at least 5–7 years of lead time.',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 81;


